Weekly backlog burndown: in the ~4 hours before the account's weekly Claude usage reset, spend the remaining credits implementing backlog items across The Borg.

This job runs headless from `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po` with the workspace root added as a working directory (see `.bin/run-scheduled-task.sh`). It is EXPECTED to die mid-run when credits run out — every phase therefore leaves durable state (commits, checked boxes) before moving on, and the plan email goes out before implementation starts.

The phases below are named, not numbered, so the paired `/backlog-burndown` command can reference them without breaking when this file is edited.

GATE — run at most once per ISO week.
Determine the current ISO week with `date +%G-W%V`. Stop and output nothing if `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown.json` exists and its `week` field equals the current ISO week.

WINDOW — abort if fired outside the pre-reset window.
The account's weekly usage reset is **Wednesday 10:59 AM local** (from `/status`); launchd fires this job Wednesday 6:59 AM. If the current local time is not Wednesday between 06:30 and 10:29 (launchd fires missed events on wake, so a sleeping Mac can delay the run), stop and output nothing — running after the reset would burn the fresh week's budget, which defeats the purpose. If the account's reset time ever changes, update this paragraph and the `weekly-wed-06-59` schedule in `.bin/install-scheduled-tasks.sh` together.

PRIORITIZE — reorder every backlog in place.
Enumerate the backlogs: `${BORG_ROOT}/BACKLOG.md` (workspace) and every `${BORG_ROOT}/repos/*/BACKLOG.md` (check the filesystem — `repos/` is git-ignored, so its children never appear in workspace git status). Reorder each file's open items by priority, preserving that file's own format and conventions (the workspace file is a flat checkbox list — reorder it highest-priority-first; a repo file with priority tiers keeps its tiers, moving items between tiers only when clearly warranted). Priority rubric: user pain in active use > bugs > security/correctness > features > nice-to-haves; weigh what unblocks other items. Do not rewrite item content. Commit each reordered file in its own repo (workspace file in the theborg repo, repo files in their repos).

CONSOLIDATE — build the run plan.
Write `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown-plan.md` (overwriting any previous run's plan): a single prioritized union of all open items across every backlog, one checkbox line per item with its source file and owning agent/repo. Items a headless run cannot do get a `needs-user:` marker with a one-line reason instead of a checkbox — anything requiring a physical device, user-only verification, credentials or purchases, app-store/publishing actions, or a destructive/irreversible operation. Order the actionable rest by the same priority rubric.

NOTIFY PLAN — email the plan before burning.
Pipe the plan into `${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/notify-email.sh c4po "Borg backlog burndown — {YYYY-MM-DD} — plan: {N} item(s), {K} needs-user"` (reads the message from stdin). Body header: same as the subject. This email is sent BEFORE implementation because the run is expected to die when credits run out; it is the user's record of what the run set out to do.

RECORD STATE — mark the week done before burning.
Write `${BORG_ROOT}/c4po/.claude/scheduled/state/c4po-backlog-burndown.json` with `{"week":"YYYY-Www","date":"YYYY-MM-DD","ts":"<ISO 8601 timestamp>","planned":<N>,"needs_user":<K>}`. `mkdir -p` the state directory first if needed. State is recorded now, not at the end, because the end may never arrive.

BURN — implement items until credits run out.
Loop over the plan top-down, one item at a time:
- Implement the item in its owning repo (workspace items under `${BORG_ROOT}`, repo items in their repo under `repos/`), following that repo's CLAUDE.md, rules, and ADR conventions.
- Verify as far as a headless run allows — run the repo's tests/build if it has them; never claim verification the item reserves for a device or the user.
- Commit in the owning repo with a clear message. Never push to any remote. Never write `cerebruh/` wiki content (read-only; the deny rules enforce this).
- Update trackers: check the item off (or move it to a Done section, per that file's convention) in its source BACKLOG.md and in the plan file; commit the tracker updates with the work.
- If an item proves infeasible headless, mark it `skipped: <reason>` in the plan file and move on.
Continue until no actionable items remain — or the session dies with the credits, which is the expected exit; the commits and checked boxes are the durable record.

WRAP — only reached if the plan empties before the credits do.
Pipe a summary (items completed / skipped / needs-user, with commit hashes) into `${BORG_ROOT}/.bin/notify-email.sh c4po "Borg backlog burndown — {YYYY-MM-DD} — {C} done, {S} skipped"`. Body header: same as the subject.
